<p><b>VY Canis Majoris</b> (<b>VY CMa</b>) is a red <a href="/wiki/Hypergiant" title="Hypergiant">hypergiant</a> <a href="/wiki/Star" title="Star">star</a> located in the constellation <a href="/wiki/Canis_Major" title="Canis Major">Canis Major</a>. With a size of up to about 2,100 <a href="/wiki/Solar_radii" title="Solar radii" class="mw-redirect">solar radii</a>, it is possibly <a href="/wiki/List_of_largest_known_stars" title="List of largest known stars">the largest known star</a> and also <a href="/wiki/List_of_most_luminous_stars" title="List of most luminous stars">one of the most luminous</a> known. It is located about 1.5 <a href="/wiki/Parsec" title="Parsec">kiloparsecs</a> (4.6×10<sup>19</sup> <a href="/wiki/Meter" title="Meter" class="mw-redirect">m</a>) or about 4,900 <a href="/wiki/Light_year" title="Light year" class="mw-redirect">light years</a> away from Earth. Unlike most stars, which occur in either <a href="/wiki/Binary_star" title="Binary star">binary</a> or <a href="/wiki/Multiple_star_system" title="Multiple star system" class="mw-redirect">multiple star systems</a>, VY CMa is a single star and does not have any stellar companions. It is categorized as a <a href="/wiki/Semiregular_variable" title="Semiregular variable" class="mw-redirect">semiregular variable</a> and has an estimated <a href="/wiki/Orbital_period" title="Orbital period">period</a> of 2,000 days.<sup id="cite_ref-Monnier1998_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Monnier1998-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
